uality in serialization**\\n\\nIf I have two different String objects containing the same content serialized separately, they'll be treated as two distinct strings. I can check the entrySet to see if it contains two entries with the same key, \\\"duplicate,\\\" yet differing identities. \\n\\nTo ensure the deserialized map correctly identifies these keys post-serialization, I can fetch the actual keys from the entrySet and assert that containsKey(new String(\\\"same\\\")) returns false, confirming they are indeed different key objects.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering serialization challenges**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to handle duplicate-value mapping and the need for serializable key/value types. Perhaps using a custom static class would help avoid extra serialization configuration? Built-in strings and arrays seem fine, and it seems like two equal strings work together. I wonder about Java serialization and whether deserialization creates distinct instances. I’ll ensure new strings are used, but I also need to be cautious about null keys/values in the map. I’ll implement dynamic access lines for serialization and consider potential reflection issues.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating serialization approach**\\n\\nI’m considering that javac likely won’t fail on warnings, but I still want to ensure my class uses raw types without generics. I wonder if avoiding generics altogether might be the way to go, especially if I use Map.Entry in a raw format. I should be able to handle serialization without direct reflection. Maybe I need a dedicated test file for this, so I’ll add one and check the repository status beforehand.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_z3Ald5r55EklPwttjnJgWLSm|fc_02edba018eb7b9450169f491b8435881a3beaaada848a8b1c2", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "git status --short", "timeout": 10}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"git status --short\",\"timeout\":10}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provid